      <text xml:space="preserve">{{for|the French mathematician known for work in the area of [[elliptic curve]]s|André Weil}}
{{Infobox scientist
|name              = Andrew Wiles
|image             = Andrew wiles1-3.jpg
|caption           = Sir Andrew John Wiles
|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1953|4|11|df=y}}
|birth_place       = [[Cambridge]], England
|nationality       = {{flag|GBR|name=British}}
|field             = [[Mathematics]]
|work_institutions = [[Princeton University]]
|alma_mater        = [[University of Oxford]]&lt;br&gt;[[University of Cambridge]]
|doctoral_advisor  = [[John Coates (mathematician)|John Coates]]
|doctoral_students = [[Manjul Bhargava]]&lt;br&gt;[[Brian Conrad]]&lt;br&gt;[[Fred Diamond]]&lt;br&gt;[[Karl Rubin]]&lt;br&gt;[[Christopher Skinner]]&lt;br&gt;[[Richard Taylor (mathematician)|Richard Taylor]]
|known_for         = Proving the [[Taniyama-Shimura Conjecture]] for semistable elliptic curves, and thereby proving [[Fermat's Last Theorem]]
|prizes            = [[Fermat Prize]] (1995)&lt;br&gt;[[Wolf Prize]] (1995/6)&lt;br&gt;[[Royal Medal]] (1996)&lt;br&gt;IMU Silver Plaque (1998)&lt;br&gt;[[Shaw Prize]] (2005)
}}
Sir '''Andrew John Wiles''' [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (born 11 April 1953)&lt;ref name=&quot;WhosWho&quot;&gt;
&quot;WILES, Sir Andrew (John)&quot;, [[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]], A &amp; C Black, January 2007&lt;/ref&gt; is a British [[mathematician]] and a professor at [[Princeton University]], specializing in [[number theory]]. He is most famous for [[Wiles' proof of Fermat's Last Theorem|proving Fermat's Last Theorem]].

==Early life and education==
Andrew Wiles is the son of [[Maurice Wiles|Maurice Frank Wiles]] (1923–2005), the [[Regius Professor of Divinity at the University of Oxford]]&lt;ref&gt;WILES, Rev. Prof. Maurice Frank, Who Was Who, A &amp; C Black, January 2007.&lt;/ref&gt; and Patricia Wiles (née Mowll). His father worked as the Chaplain at [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]], for the years 1952–55. Wiles was born in [[Cambridge, England]], in 1953, and he  attended King's College School, Cambridge, and [[The Leys School, Cambridge]]. 

Wiles discovered Fermat's Last Theorem on his way home from school when he was 10 years old. He stopped by his local library where he found a book about the theorem.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/proof/wiles.html&lt;/ref&gt; Puzzled by the fact that the statement of the theorem was so easy that he, a ten-year old, could understand it, he decided to be the first person to prove it. However, he soon realized that his knowledge of mathematics was too small, so he abandoned his childhood dream, until 1986, when he heard that [[Kenneth Alan Ribet|Ribet]] had proved [[Jean-Pierre Serre|Serre]]'s [[Ribet's theorem|ε-conjecture]] and therefore established a link between Fermat's Last Theorem and the [[Modularity theorem|Taniyama-Shimura conjecture]].

Wiles earned his [[bachelor's degree]] in mathematics in 1974 after his study at [[Merton College, Oxford]], and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in 1980, after his research at [[Clare College, Cambridge]].

After a stay at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] in [[New Jersey]] in 1981, Wiles became a professor at [[Princeton University]]. In 1985–86, Wiles was a [[Guggenheim Fellow]] at the [[Institut des Hautes Études Scientifiques]] near Paris and at the [[École Normale Supérieure]]. From 1988 to 1990, Wiles was a [[Royal Society]] Research Professor at [[Oxford University]], and then he returned to Princeton.

In October 2009 it was announced that Wiles would again become a Royal Society Research Professor at Oxford in 2011.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ox.ac.uk/media/news_stories/2009/091015.html Oxford to welcome new Royal Society Professors]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Mathematical career==
Wiles's graduate research was guided by [[John Coates (mathematician)|John Coates]] beginning in the summer of 1975. Together these colleagues worked on the arithmetic of [[elliptic curve]]s with [[complex multiplication]] by the methods of [[Iwasawa theory]]. He further worked with [[Barry Mazur]] on the main conjecture of Iwasawa theory over the [[rational number]]s, and soon afterward, he generalized this result to [[totally real field]]s.

==The proof of Fermat's Last Theorem==
{{main|Wiles' proof of Fermat's Last Theorem}}

Starting in the summer of 1986, based on successive progress of the previous few years of [[Gerhard Frey]], [[Jean-Pierre Serre]] and [[Ken Ribet]], Wiles realised that a proof of a limited form of the [[modularity theorem]] might then be in reach. He dedicated all of his research time to this problem in relative secrecy. In 1993, he presented his proof to the public for the first time at a conference in Cambridge. In August 1993, however, it turned out that the proof contained a gap. In desperation, Andrew Wiles tried to fill in this gap, but found out that the error he had made was a very fundamental one. According to Wiles, the crucial idea for circumventing, rather than closing this gap, came to him on 19 September 1994. Together with his former student [[Richard Taylor (mathematician)|Richard Taylor]], he published a second paper which circumvented the gap and thus completed the proof. Both papers were published in 1995 in a special volume of the Annals of Mathematics.

==Recognition by the media==
His proof of [[Fermat's Last Theorem]] has stood up to the scrutiny of the world's mathematical experts. Wiles was interviewed for an episode of the [[British Broadcasting Corporation]]'s documentary series ''[[Horizon (BBC TV series)|Horizon]]'' that focused on Fermat's Last Theorem. This was renamed &quot;The Proof&quot;, and it was made an episode of the [[Public Broadcasting Service]]'s television science TV series ''[[Nova (TV series)|Nova]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|year=1997|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/proof/|title=[[NOVA (TV series)|NOVA Online]]: The Proof|publisher=[[WGBH-TV|WGBH]]|accessdate=2006-05-03}}&lt;/ref&gt; He is a foreign member of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]] since 1996. He remains a citizen of the United Kingdom.&lt;ref name=WhosWho /&gt;

==Family==
Wiles is married to Nada Canaan Wiles, who earned her Ph.D. in [[microbiology]] from [[Princeton University]] in [[New Jersey]], and they have three daughters: Clare, Kate and Olivia.&lt;ref name=WhosWho/&gt; He currently lives in Princeton, New Jersey.

==Awards==
Wiles has been awarded several major prizes in mathematics and science:
* [[Whitehead Prize|Junior Whitehead Prize]] of the  [[London Mathematical Society|LMS]] (1988)&lt;ref name=&quot;WhosWho&quot; /&gt;
* [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (1989)&lt;ref name=&quot;WhosWho&quot; /&gt;
* [[Schock Prize]] (1995)
* [[Fermat Prize]] (1995)
* [[Wolf Prize in Mathematics|Wolf Prize]] (1995/6)
* [[NAS Award in Mathematics]] from the National Academy of Sciences (1996)&lt;ref name=NASMath&gt;{{cite web|title=NAS Award in Mathematics|url=http://www.nasonline.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AWARDS_mathematics|publisher=National Academy of Sciences|accessdate=13 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/notices/199607/comm-wiles.pdf Wiles Receives NAS Award in Mathematics] July 1996&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Royal Medal]] (1996)
* [[Ostrowski Prize]] (1996)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/notices/199606/people.pdf Wiles Receives Ostrowski Prize] June 1996&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/notices/199807/fyi.pdf Correction] 1998&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Cole Prize]] (1997)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=1997 Cole Prize, Notices of the AMS|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/199703/comm-cole.pdf|accessdate=2008-04-13|format=PDF}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* Wolfskehl Prize (1997)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/notices/199710/barner.pdf Paul Wolfskehl and the Wolfskehl Prize] October 1997&lt;/ref&gt; – see [[Paul Wolfskehl]]
* A silver plaque from the [[International Mathematical Union]] (1998) recognizing his achievements, in place of the [[Fields Medal]], which is restricted to those under 40 (Wiles was born in 1953 and proved the theorem in 1994)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/featurecolumn/archive/wiles.html Andrew J. Wiles Awarded the &quot;IMU Silver Plaque&quot;]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.princeton.edu/pr/home/98/0828-wiles/hmcap.html Andrew Wiles receives special tribute] August 28, 1998&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[King Faisal Foundation#King Faisal International Prize|King Faisal Prize]] (1998)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/notices/199805/comm-wiles.pdf Andrew Wiles Receives Faisal Prize]&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Clay Research Award]] (1999)
* [[Shaw Prize]] (2005)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ams.org/notices/200508/comm-shaw.pdf Wiles Receives 2005 Shaw Prize] September 2005&lt;/ref&gt;
* Pythagoras Award (Croton, 2004)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.premiopitagora.it/ Premio Pitagora]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Public honours==
* The [[asteroid]] [[9999 Wiles]] was named for Wiles in 1999.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser|url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=9999+Wiles|accessdate=2009-05-11}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* Wiles was appointed to the rank of [[Order of the British Empire|Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in the United Kingdom in 2000.&lt;ref&gt;{{LondonGazette |issue=55710 |date=31 December 1999 |startpage=34 |supp=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==In popular culture==
* Wiles was mentioned in an episode of ''Star Trek'' for his proof of Fermat's Last Theorem.
*He was also mentioned in [[Stieg Larsson]]'s second book of the Millennium trilogy ''[[The Girl Who Played With Fire]]'', and also the third, ''[[The Girl Who Kicked the Hornets' Nest]]''. Wiles was credited with solving Fermat's Last Theorem when the female protagonist [[Lisbeth Salander]] attempted to solve it.
* [[Tom Lehrer]]'s song ''That's Mathematics'' mentions that Wiles &quot;confirms what Fermat / Jotted down in that margin / Which could've used some enlargin'.&quot;

